<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-03-28T17:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-03-28T17:00:00-05:00" n="415" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d415">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">824.00/1930: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Chargé in Bolivia</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Woodward</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-03-28T18:00:00-04:00">March 28,
                                    1944—6 p.m.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>361. From Ambassador Boal.<note n="69" xml:id="d415fn69">Temporarily in
                                Washington.</note> Your 697, March 20.<note n="70" xml:id="d415fn70">Not printed.</note> Is Junta’s decree convoking elections based on
                            constitutional grounds? If so, please cite pertinent passages of
                            Constitution. Has Junta declared adherence to Constitution? If so, which
                            one? [Boal.]</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>